article.headline: Comets improve to 4-1
article.linkText: Swoopes' last-minute layup lifts Comets past Mercury
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Sheryl Swoopes scored only three points in the
second half, but she managed to find a way to keep the Houston
Comets undefeated at home.

Swoopes' layup with 25.7 seconds left lifted the Comets to a
59-57 win over the Phoenix Mercury on Saturday.

After tweaking her left ankle just after halftime, Swoopes
didn't score again until she made a free throw with less than a
minute to go. Then she hit the game-winning shot to finish with 10
points on 4-of-12 shooting -- well below her season average of 25
points -- and five assists.

"I am so proud of this team right now," Swoopes said. "We
didn't give up and found a way to pull it out. It was ugly for me
at times, but the bottom line is that we fought to get the win here
at home."

The Comets won their third home game and improved to 4-1
overall.

Dominique Canty made seven of her 16 shots and led the Comets
with 15 points. The Mercury had a chance to send the game into
overtime, but Ashley Robinson missed a layup with 0.9 seconds
remaining.

Anna DeForge led Phoenix with a game-high 20 points and Plenette
Pierson added 12 as the Mercury dropped to 1-5.

Leading scorer Diana Taurasi was just 2-for-9 from the floor and
scored a season-low four points. She was 0-for-5 from 3-point
range.

"She wasn't focused tonight," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said
of Taurasi. "Her performance was below par. But toward the end of
the second half, she played a quality game."

The Mercury committed a team-record 28 turnovers, but
out-rebounded the Comets 36-17.

"How can you get out-rebounded like that and still win the
game?" said Comets coach Van Chancellor. "That might be the most
I've ever seen a team out-rebounded and still get a win."

After the Mercury took a 55-51 lead with 7:09 left, the Comets
went on an 8-2 run to close out the game.

Phoenix committed 19 turnovers in the first half and trailed by
as many as 13 points in the opening period.

After Pierson hit a 10-foot jumper to make it 20-16 midway
through the first half, the Comets went on a 17-6 run to take a
35-22 lead.

"You can't have 28 turnovers in somebody else's gym and expect
to win," DeForge said. "We made a run in the second half, but it
wasn't enough. We rebounded really well tonight, but we've got to
get other people involved."
